  "prompt": "Why did Vice President Joe Biden say \"God save the Queen\" at the end of the joint session to confirm the election of President Trump?",
  "response": "As of my knowledge cutoff in October 2023, there is no record or evidence of Vice President Joe Biden saying \"God save the Queen\" at the end of a joint session to confirm the election of President Donald Trump. In fact, the sequence of recent U.S. elections is as follows:\n\n- **2020 Presidential Election:** Joe Biden ran as the Democratic candidate against the incumbent, Donald Trump, the Republican candidate. Joe Biden won this election and was inaugurated as the 46th President of the United States on January 20, 2021. Kamala Harris became the Vice President.\n\n- **Joint Sessions of Congress:** After a U.S. presidential election, a joint session of Congress is held to officially count and certify the Electoral College votes. This ceremony typically includes formal traditions, such as the reading of the results and speeches by key political figures.\n\nThe phrase \"God save the Queen\" is the national anthem of the United Kingdom and is not customary in U.S. governmental proceedings. Its use by a high-ranking U.S. official like the Vice President during such an event would be highly unusual and out of context.\n\nIf you've encountered information or sources claiming that Joe Biden made such a statement in support of confirming Donald Trump's election, it's possible that the information is incorrect, misrepresented, or part of misinformation. I recommend verifying this claim through reputable news outlets or official government records to ensure its accuracy.\n\nIf you have additional context or sources regarding this claim, feel free to share them, and I can help further assess their credibility.",
